### Reflection

Now that you have created a software component from scratch, it's time to
reflect on that process as well as take some time to think about your
growth as a developer. Below, you will find a series of reflection prompts.
Take some time to fill them out honestly.

> A common gripe that students express is how much they feel the work they do
> in class fails to map to the real world. Now that you've had a chance to
> complete the portfolio project, how much better (or worse) do you think you
> understand software development and why?

I feel like I understand software development more as now I can see all the parts
that go into it. It's not like one of the projects we are assigned in this I had
to code more than one file, have test cases, show demos which is way more steps
than I have had in the past. This just shows how much there is to do in a software
development project and it's not as simple as just writing some code. You have to
think, solve problems when the code fails and be creative.

> Also, did the portfolio project surface any gaps in your own knowledge of
> software development. If so, what are those gaps and how did you address them?

I feel like sometimes I had trouble deciding what I wanted to do or how to complete
a task. I did some outside research to figure out what should it look like. I feel
like there wasn't too many gaps in my knowledge since we learned about the kernel
and secondary parts before. One thing though is I never used Git like branches and
merging so it was a bit of a different challenge but overall it's easy to use.

> Finally, as a part of completing the portfolio project, to what extent has
> your perspective of software development changed, if at all? In other words,
> is software development something you still enjoy? If not, why not?

Personally my perspective hasn't changed I still don't know if it's something I
will choose to do in my future job. I did enjoy creating my own ideas but I also
felt like I was stressing myself out sometimes like I couldn't think of what I needed
to add. It's also hard to decide if like I want to do something like this in the
future in a job because with jobs you aren't alone so it wouldn't be exactly this
same scenario.

> One of the challenges of completing the portfolio project is picking up a lot
> of skills on your own. Some of these skills are, of course, software skills.
> However, there are plenty of other skills you may have picked up through
> this process. Therefore, the first question is what skills did you pick up
> through this process?

I would say I improved my understanding on how to create and design an object. For
example I got practice in making Kernel and Secondary methods and classes. I obviously
made test files during projects but this time it felt different as I was also
making my own methods to call tests on. I also gained experience with Git with
branches and merging so now I know how it works. I also got better at debugging and
fixing errors that were either showing or kind of hidden. I also showed that I'm
able to follow a multiple step project.

> The follow-up question is: could you rephrase these skills you picked up
> as bullet points that you could put on a resume? Try it below.

- Designed and implemented a Java component using kernel and secondary
- Made JUnit test files to make sure the component works correctly
- Able to follow multiple step project to its full goal
- Used Git for version control using different branches and merging
- Debugged and resolved errors either shown by checkstyle or found on my own
- Improved problem-solving and creativity making a component that I wanted.

> Next, how has working on this project affected your career trajectory?
> In other words, do you now hate the topic you picked? Or, are you even more
> interested in it? Both outcomes are valuable to your personal development.

I love the topic I picked the reason I chose a basketball stats tracker is because
I enjoy watching basketball. It would be a dream to have some sort of sport job
and connecting it to computer science in the future. I have to do some research
on what this may look like because I don't have a clear idea. I would say I am more
interested in it but I already was so not too much different.

> Finally, consider the skills you've picked up and your current career
> trajectory. What are some things you could do to continue on your
> career trajectory? Also, who are some mentors you could contact to help
